<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="569" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,823,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">
<taxonomicName box="[151,275,824,848]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Bucardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,275,824,848]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Bucardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was introduced by 
<bibRefCitation author="Gray" box="[498,639,823,848]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Gray, J. E. (1853) A revision of the genera of some of the families of conchifera or bivalves shells. The Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 2, 11, 33 - 44." type="journal article" year="1853">Gray (1853)</bibRefCitation>
, with the following diagnosis: &quot;Shell subglobose, costate, hinder gape narrow and strongly toothed on the hinder edge&quot;. He included three species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Bruguiere, 1789" authorityName="Bruguiere" authorityYear="1789" box="[1015,1399,860,885]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Cardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ringens">
<emphasis box="[1015,1206,860,884]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Cardium ringens</emphasis>
Bruguière, 1789
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="G. B. Sowerby, 1833" authorityName="G. B. Sowerby" authorityYear="1833" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Cardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="procerum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">C. procerum</emphasis>
G. B. Sowerby, 1833
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus, 1758" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[607,912,895,920]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Cardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="unedo">
<emphasis box="[607,716,896,920]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">C. unedo</emphasis>
Linnaeus, 1758
</taxonomicName>
however, the 
<typeStatus box="[1094,1142,896,920]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName box="[1252,1377,896,919]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Cardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ringens">
<emphasis box="[1252,1377,896,919]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">C. ringens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was subsequently designated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Vest" box="[476,613,932,957]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Vest, W. von (1875) Ueber die genera Adacna, Monodacna und Didacna Eaichwald und deren Stellung im System. Jahrbucher der Deutschen Malakozoologischen Gesellschaft, 2, 309 - 225." type="journal volume" year="1875">Vest (1875)</bibRefCitation>
. It also became the 
<typeStatus box="[849,897,933,957]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">type</typeStatus>
species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1032,1185,932,956]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Ringicardium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1032,1185,932,956]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Ringicardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Fischer" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Fischer, P. (1887) Manuel de Conchyliologie et de Paleontologie conchyliologique ou Histoire naturelle des Mollusques vivants et fossiles. Librairie F. Savy, Paris, 1369 pp." type="book" year="1887">Fischer (1887</bibRefCitation>
: 1037) as a section (subgenus) of 
<taxonomicName box="[599,698,968,992]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Cardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[599,698,968,992]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Cardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,823,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">
<bibRefCitation author="Keen" box="[199,343,1004,1029]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Keen, A. M. (1969) Superfamily Cardiacea Lamarck, 1809. In: Moore, R. C. (Ed.), Treatise on invertebrate paleontology. Part N. Vol. 2. Mollusca 6. The Geological Society of America, Inc. e the University of Kansas, Bivalvia, pp. 583 - 594." type="journal article" year="1969">Keen (1969)</bibRefCitation>
considered 
<taxonomicName box="[484,607,1004,1028]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Bucardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[484,607,1004,1028]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Bucardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a subgenus of 
<taxonomicName box="[821,920,1004,1028]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Cardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[821,920,1004,1028]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Cardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with a distribution from Lower Miocene to Recent, in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[388,464,1040,1063]" name="France" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">France</collectingCountry>
and West Africa, and the following diagnosis: &quot;Posterior ribs strongly digitate, no posterior gape&quot;.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="569" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,823,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">
<bibRefCitation author="Popov" box="[199,356,1112,1136]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Popov, S. V. (1977) Mikrostruktura rakoviny i sistematika kardiid. Trudy Paleontologicheskogo Instituta Akademii Nauk SSSR, 153, 1 - 124 [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1977">Popov (1977)</bibRefCitation>
, in a systematic arrangement mainly based on shell structure, considered 
<taxonomicName box="[1200,1324,1112,1136]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Bucardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1200,1324,1112,1136]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Bucardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a distinct genus, subdivided into three genera, in addition to the nominotypical one: 
<taxonomicName authority="Iredale, 1829" authorityName="Iredale" authorityYear="1829" box="[1101,1432,1148,1173]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Vepricardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1101,1252,1148,1172]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Vepricardium</emphasis>
Iredale, 1829
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Popov, 1977" authorityName="Popov" authorityYear="1977" box="[151,473,1184,1208]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Europicardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,320,1184,1208]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Europicardium</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Popov" box="[329,473,1184,1208]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Popov, S. V. (1977) Mikrostruktura rakoviny i sistematika kardiid. Trudy Paleontologicheskogo Instituta Akademii Nauk SSSR, 153, 1 - 124 [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1977">Popov, 1977</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and, dubitatively, the extinct 
<taxonomicName authority="Stewart, 1930" authorityName="Stewart" authorityYear="1930" box="[819,1120,1184,1208]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Agnocardia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[819,950,1184,1208]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Agnocardia</emphasis>
Stewart, 1930
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[1131,1322,1184,1208]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Cardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ringens">
<emphasis box="[1131,1322,1184,1208]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Cardium ringens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remained the only species assigned to 
<emphasis box="[478,502,1221,1244]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">B.</emphasis>
(
<taxonomicName box="[520,643,1220,1244]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Bucardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[520,643,1220,1244]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Bucardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Popov's classification has found no general agreement (
<bibRefCitation author="Keen" box="[1303,1431,1220,1244]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Keen, A. M. (1980) The pelecypod family Cardiidae: a taxonomic summary. Tulane Studies in Geology and Paleontology, 16, 1 - 40." type="journal article" year="1980">Keen 1980</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Schneider" box="[151,329,1255,1280]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Schneider, J. A. (2002) Phylogeny of cardiid bivalves (cockles and giant clams): revision of the Cardiinae and the importance of fossils in explaining disjunct biogeographical distributions. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 136, 321 - 369. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1096 - 3642.2002.00030. x" type="journal article" year="2002">Schneider 2002</bibRefCitation>
; ter 
<bibRefCitation author="Poorten" box="[377,529,1255,1280]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Poorten, J. J. ter (2005) Outline of a systematic index - Recent Cardiidae (Lamarck, 1809). VISAYA net. Available from: http: // www. conchology. be /? t = 702 &amp; year = 2005 &amp; volume = 14 &amp; vnet = 1316 (accessed 11 October 2016)" type="journal article" year="2005">Poorten 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="La" box="[541,708,1255,1280]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="La Perna, R. (2016) A revision of the genus Europicardium Popov, 1977 (Bivalvia: Cardiidae) from the European Neogene: tracking palaeogeography and climate changes. Journal of Systematic Palaeontology. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 14772019.2016.1170733" type="book chapter" year="2016">La Perna 2016</bibRefCitation>
), but both 
<taxonomicName box="[826,977,1256,1280]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Vepricardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[826,977,1256,1280]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Vepricardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1032,1156,1256,1280]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Bucardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1032,1156,1256,1280]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Bucardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are currently included in the subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[311,420,1292,1317]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cardiinae">Cardiinae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Schneider" box="[434,612,1292,1317]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Schneider, J. A. (2002) Phylogeny of cardiid bivalves (cockles and giant clams): revision of the Cardiinae and the importance of fossils in explaining disjunct biogeographical distributions. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 136, 321 - 369. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1096 - 3642.2002.00030. x" type="journal article" year="2002">Schneider 2002</bibRefCitation>
) whereas 
<taxonomicName box="[725,894,1292,1316]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Europicardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[725,894,1292,1316]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Europicardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sister taxon of the clade 
<taxonomicName box="[1198,1297,1292,1316]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Cardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1198,1297,1292,1316]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Cardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName box="[1312,1435,1292,1316]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Bucardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1312,1435,1292,1316]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Bucardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Herrera" box="[158,377,1327,1352]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Herrera, N. D., Poorten, J. J. ter, Bieler, R., Mikkelsen, P. M., Strong, E. E., Jablonski, D. &amp; Steppan, J. S. (2015) Molecular phylogenetics and historical biogeography amid shifting continents in the cockles and giant clams (Bivalvia: Cardiidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 93, 94 - 106. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2015.07.013" type="journal article" year="2015">
Herrera e 
<emphasis box="[265,302,1328,1352]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">t al</emphasis>
. 2015
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,823,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">
<taxonomicName box="[199,413,1364,1388]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Bucardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ringens">
<emphasis box="[199,413,1364,1388]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Bucardium ringens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[428,492,1364,1389]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) has an almost orbicular shell shape, slightly higher than large, sub-equilateral, with a long, barely convex, gently sloping antero-dorsal margin, and a very short postero-dorsal one. The maximum size is about 
<quantity box="[250,331,1436,1461]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" unit="mm" value="50.0">50 mm</quantity>
in antero-posterior length (pers. comm., ter Poorten 2016). The sculpture consists of radial ribs, much finer anteriorly, wider and stronger on the remaining shell surface. Along the posterior margin, the radial ribs give origin to short, strong digitations (
<figureCitation box="[587,649,1508,1533]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
C) that are almost interlocking when the shell is closed and occupying most of the posterior shell gape (
<figureCitation box="[518,582,1543,1568]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
E).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,823,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">
The fine anterior ribs are symmetrically triangular in cross section, then they become more and more asymmetrical (saw-tooth shaped) toward the posterior margin, with a wider, slightly convex anterior slope and a narrower, stepped posterior one (
<figureCitation box="[522,585,1652,1677]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
A, C). Near the posterior margin, the ribs are distinctly ridged and strongly asymmetrical, forming the digitate margin with their projections (
<figureCitation box="[896,961,1687,1712]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
C). The radial interspaces are narrow, flat and smooth, except for the posterior area, where they are narrow and deep. Well distinct crescent-shaped growth striae are present on the posterior ribs (
<figureCitation box="[591,655,1759,1784]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
C). No sculpture, except for growth striae, occurs on the ribs. Details on the hinge of 
<taxonomicName box="[327,442,1797,1820]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Bucardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ringens">
<emphasis box="[327,442,1797,1820]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">B. ringens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were reported and commented by 
<bibRefCitation author="Schneider" box="[831,1135,1796,1821]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Schneider, J. A. (2002) Phylogeny of cardiid bivalves (cockles and giant clams): revision of the Cardiinae and the importance of fossils in explaining disjunct biogeographical distributions. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 136, 321 - 369. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1096 - 3642.2002.00030. x" type="journal article" year="2002">Schneider (2002: fig. 12B)</bibRefCitation>
. In particular, he remarked the occurrence of striae on the lunular flap, a character shared with 
<taxonomicName box="[940,1038,1832,1856]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Cardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[940,1038,1832,1856]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Cardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and some other 
<taxonomicName box="[1235,1344,1831,1856]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cardiinae">Cardiinae</taxonomicName>
genera. Schneider's illustration is not particularly clear, but the ridges on the lunular flap consist of a short, slightly oblique and somewhat irregular crenulation of the dorsal margin, more or less extending onto the lunular flap (
<figureCitation box="[1299,1362,1903,1928]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
G, H).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,823,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">
The species has a wide distribution in West Africa, from 
<collectingCountry box="[847,970,1940,1965]" name="Mauritania" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Mauritania</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[1008,1090,1940,1965]" name="Angola" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Angola</collectingCountry>
(about 20°N–20°S), including the 
<collectingCountry box="[196,329,1976,2001]" name="Cape Verde" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Cape Verde</collectingCountry>
Islands and 
<collectingCountry box="[482,757,1976,2001]" name="Sao Tome and Principe" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">
<collectingRegion box="[482,598,1976,2000]" country="Sao Tome and Principe" name="Sao Tome" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">São Tomé</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[661,757,1976,2001]" country="Sao Tome and Principe" name="Principe" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Príncipe</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
, in 
<quantity box="[805,921,1976,2001]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.75" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" unit="m" value="57.5" valueMax="100.0" valueMin="15.0">15–100 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Fischer-Piette" box="[940,1167,1976,2001]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Fischer-Piette, E. (1977) Revision des Cardiidae (Mollusques, Lamellibraches). Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire naturelle, New Series, A, 101, 1 - 212." type="journal article" year="1977">Fischer-Piette 1977</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Voskuil" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Voskuil, R. P. &amp; Onverwagt, W. J. R. (1989) Inventarisation of the Recent European and West African Cardiidae (Mollusca, Bivalvia). Gloria Maris, 28, 49 - 96." type="journal article" year="1989">Voskuil &amp; Onverwagt 1989</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
